Clouston et al. (2014b)

Age-, race-, and sex- specific mortality rates for suicide among US residents 25 years or older (1968–2009) were derived from death certificate and population data from the National Center for Health Statistics. Change in associations between county-level SES and suicide (prevention knowledge developed) mortality were compared.

Suicide mortality rates were initially similar in higher- and lower-SES counties but shifted upon the distribution of antidepressant medications (SSRIs). By 2009, the difference in mortality between counties with SES one SD above compared with one SD below average had grown substantially.

“We found support for the theory that SES based disparities in suicide arose with the widespread dispersal of SSRIs, which were concentrated in areas of higher SES.” (Clouston et al. 2014b, p. 702)

