Spillovers refer to the fact that “individuals are embedded in social relations in which other people also value their health, and the actions of other people have consequences that accrue differently to people of different social positions” (Freese & Lutfey 2011, p. 72). It follows that people can derive a health benefit from the actions of others if, for example, those others keep noise and pollution away from where one lives or negotiate a strong preventive health care health package in one’s place of work. In instances such as these, neighbors or coworkers benefit without taking any action themselves. In this work, Freese & Lutfey draw on Bourdieu (1979) to define habitus as “basic dispositions of interpretation and action that reflect an actor’s social position.” The idea that habitus shapes health decisions outside of conscious, directed use of resources is supported by Cockerham’s (2005) health lifestyle theory, in which Cockerham describes habitus as a map that routinely guides action so that actions can be carried out nearly automatically: “They are simply habitual ways of acting when performing routine tasks” (Cockerham 2005, p. 61). Institutional processing was proposed as a third metamechanism to integrate “the agentic, dynamic action” of institutions that facilitate or block actions of individuals seeking to enhance health. This concept coheres with Bird & Rieker’s (2008) more general concept of constrained choices, which we subsequently consider as it relates to FCT.
While from very early on, FCT emphasized the role of contextual factors operating in addition to and outside of individual action (Phelan et al. 2004), spillovers, habitus, and institutional processing are extremely useful for their precision in specifying some of the processes through which contextual factors operate. However, it would be unfortunate if these concepts detracted from the importance of resources by indicating that resources are just one component. People are not accidently situated in neighborhoods or networks where spillovers occur, in social contexts where healthy dispositions (habitus) can be developed, or in institutions that can be expected to differentially process them. They may not nestle themselves into circumstances like these because of health concerns, but they do regularly use resources to enhance their location in these respects. For these reasons we argue that resources should retain a primary position in FCT.
Collective Health Agency
Whereas Freese & Lutfey (2011) usefully pointed out that high-SES people might benefit from processes that do not involve the active use of resources, we thought it important to expand and clarify the importance of resource use at the collective level. We call this “collective health agency.” The idea is that collections of people propitiously situated in societal hierarchies will share interests in good schools, safe parks, crime-free neighborhoods, excellent medical facilities, and other such resources. Simply put, powerful people protect members of their communities by securing and sharing flexible resources within their communities. These health-relevant interests are likely to join together, pooling resources of knowledge, money, power, prestige, and beneficial social connections to achieve desired ends. They collectively and agentically insist on better health conditions in their schools, neighborhoods, cities, or nation-states. As they push for these benefits, they set themselves apart, thereby creating sharp inequalities in the social determinants of health that reliably yield inequalities in health outcomes.
As an example, consider the fact that in many instances, researchers have relied on individuallevel factors such as educational attainment as indicators of SES (Masters et al. 2015), while others have relied on regional indicators of SES within a country (Saldana-Ruiz et al. 2013). While these are related, we need to ask the extent to which the risk of mortality at the individual level is driven by individuals seeking out protective factors and avoiding risky ones (Montez et al. 2019) or by a collective agency—the communal pooling of resources from public or other private
