(Dyer 2019) and widespread movements to legalize the use, perceived as less harmful, of recreational and medical marijuana (Cerdá et al. 2020). The results of these efforts clearly have the potential to, on the one hand, provide help to some community members while, on the other hand, effectively pushing others down and away. The differences between these policy initiatives can be construed in terms of some of the concepts we have introduced. First, we see what we have called collective agency in operation: The collective agency of White elites was marshalled in the crack epidemic to criminalize addiction, and in the opioid epidemic to push for treatment and decriminalization. Second—and perhaps lying behind the collective agency exercised in each circumstance—we see processes consistent with the idea that racism is a fundamental cause of health inequalities.
Precision Medicine
The application of FCT to precision medicine is increasingly important, as resources spent to develop highly specific treatments for relatively common diseases are more likely to benefit those with the most resources or those suffering from diseases with large at-risk populations. At the nexus of social, epidemiological, and biological research, there is an increasing interest in omics— a branch of biology that is focused on the in-depth characterization of a single complex system, such as the genome—and its focus on precision medicine. For example, research seeking to control for genetic factors using twin studies has also reported SES inequalities in more preventable diseases, even when holding genetics constant (Ericsson et al. 2019), while other researchers used Mendelian randomization to examine causal hypotheses linking polygenic risk scores for social phenomena to health outcomes (Davey Smith & Ebrahim 2003). Some have argued that higher education was associated with improved body mass and reduced risk of smoking both via direct effects of education and through changes in the genetic propensity for obesity and smoking (Mann et al. 2019). Still, other research highlights the role of epigenetics as a biological mechanism facilitating intergenerational transfer of inequality in health ( Jadotte 2019), essentially encoding SESrelated information into the genome (King et al. 2015). However, omics results are also shaped by parental circumstances, thereby modulating the impact of polygenic risk on outcomes including body mass (Liu & Guo 2015). This work supports the FCT hypothesis in suggesting that the effects of SES may have even genetic implications, but much more work is needed that considers the extent to which health inequalities are affected by the unequal influence of genetics across places and times.
COVID-19
Would a disease that did not exist when FCT was developed be shaped in a manner the theory might predict? The COVID-19 pandemic has caused a global emergency that is particularly interesting to consider through the lens of the previously mentioned stage of disease framework introduced by Clouston et al. (2016), with its four stages: natural variation, increasing inequalities, decreasing or stable inequalities, and reducing inequalities. We rapidly noted that the first two stages seem relevant to COVID-19 (Clouston et al. 2021)—a first stage in which people cannot protect themselves because they have insufficient knowledge and a second stage when knowledge grows, and intervention becomes possible in high-SES communities.
In the early stages of the COVID-19 pandemic, the virus was transported to the United States from affected countries via prosperous elites during international travel. Cruise ships and ski resorts were sites of early outbreaks when the disease was spreading among travelers. Simply put, there was insufficient knowledge about the reach of the disease, thereby diminishing the possibility of an effective defense. As knowledge of the threat grew, individuals began to
