implement tried and true public health measures to combat the disease such as sheltering in place, social distancing, and handwashing, thereby allowing the same social elites to reduce withincommunity transmission and to reduce further infection in their social circles. Concurrently, disadvantaged individuals and predominantly minority populations were much more likely to be classified as essential workers, live in crowded circumstances, and work in jobs with minimal worker protections. These circumstances forced individuals to remain in high-risk situations. This redirection of exposure appears particularly concerning since a lifetime of adversity often places vulnerable individuals at elevated risk of one or more health conditions (Langenberg et al. 2006) that may be risk factors for unfavorable COVID-19 outcomes (Zhou et al. 2020).
Once an individual is infected, inequalities may also arise because higher SES provides improved access to well-resourced and knowledgeable medical staff (Arabi et al. 2020), who may encourage patients to receive treatment promptly when the disease is most treatable. The contexts in which higher-SES individuals are treated may also be better at controlling transmission within the hospital while experiencing an influx of new patients (Meng et al. 2020, Singer et al. 2020). Concurrently, in a pandemic characterized by lockdowns, patients with fewer resources and who are managing chronic conditions will have markedly worse care (Khilnani et al. 2020). Additionally, vaccines are now being deployed globally, with early reports indicating the potential for global inequalities to emerge as rich countries purchase most of the vaccines, while reports from within the United States include early evidence of health disparities emerging (Painter et al. 2021). Vaccine deployment has long been a topic of interest in FCT research. For example, SES inequalities in vaccine interest and uptake in the United States (Polonijo & Carpiano 2013, Polonijo et al. 2016) and other work showing inequalities in vaccination completion by SES in a global context (Clouston et al. 2014a). Finally, the ability to avoid COVID-19 will likely be compounded by the long-term consequences of the disease. In this effort, we might anticipate that some communities and, within those communities, some individuals will have more ready access to vaccination and that SES disparities will emerge. In sum, FCT and stage of disease concepts are applicable to the COVID-19 pandemic and could be useful guides for anticipating and reducing future inequalities.
CONCLUSION
What do we think about after 25 years of FCT? FCT remains an important approach because it seeks not to legitimate the extant hierarchical structure by identifying ways in which those who are disadvantaged fail to be healthy, but instead seeks to focus attention on understanding how the powerful secure health and avoid illness while sometimes redistributing illness-causing and health-depleting exposures to communities with less power. FCT has benefited dramatically from elaborations and extensions of the theory since its formulation. Among these are (a) the stage of disease formulation that points out that not only are mechanisms replaced in a fundamental relationship but so are diseases as well; (b) the metamechanisms formulation that specifies alternatives to the purposive use of resources in creating a fundamental relationship; and (c) the concept, crystalized in the current review as collective agency, that underscores the importance of resources deployed at a collective level. The theory has also been extended to include racism and stigma as fundamental causes that are related to multiple disease outcomes and plausibly recreate healthharmful mechanisms over time. Finally, following the concept of countervailing mechanisms, we introduced competitive valuations and also drew on constrained choices theory to indicate circumstances in which FCT processes might operate differently.
In this context, FCT has helped us to understand the presence, emergence, and depletion of social inequalities in health across decades and over a broad range of outcomes. Additionally, FCT has helped characterize and contextualize changes that have emerged and provided a foundation
