for understanding new mechanisms as they arose. This has helped many better understand the impact that SES has on life expectancy and the importance of considering social and biological factors when testing and promoting interventions that seek to improve health (Gutin & Hummer 2021). In providing this focal element, FCT helps us predict and understand the risk of new diseases and helps us understand resurgences or second waves of older diseases. In so doing, FCT reminds us that the potential for SES, racism, and stigma to influence a disease outcome should become a familiar refrain in health research. FCT has helped to advance, and has also benefited from, an increasing recognition that social inequalities are indeed powerful drivers of the determinants and distribution of disease. The fact that the theory has been further developed, clarified, and tested over the past ten years suggests the possibility that the next decade will yield more advances. This review concludes that to catalyze the next decade of research in further elaborating and extending FCT, perhaps as suggested above, into new approaches to testing and novel topics to examine. However, while these emerging topics are likely to be of long-term interest, it is worth highlighting that many topics have the potential for much more discussion. Even after 25 years of conceptualization and research, there remain crucial questions to ask and other topics to address.
